WHAT IS STACK?
A stack is called a Last-In-First-Out (LIFO) collection of items. 
This means that the last item added (pushed) is the first item 
removed (popped).
A stack is a sequence of items in which elements are accessible 
only from one end, called the top.
Operations:
• PUSH – Insert an item into the stack  
• POP   – Remove an item from the stack
Example 
of Stack-
Engineer dude learning
Engineer dude learning
Enginee
Engin
Engin
Engin

A stack is a linear data structure where elements can be added or 
removed from only one end, called the top. When you remove elements, 
they come out in the reverse order of how they were added.
A stack works on the LIFO (Last-In, First-Out) principle. This means the element 
added last is removed first.
There are two main operations in a stack:
PUSH: Used to add an element to the top of the stack.
POP: Used to remove an element from the top of the stack.
STACKS AS ADT :
