TYPES OF STACK
Fixed (Static) Size Stack   
A fixed size stack has a predefined capacity.
Once it becomes full, no more elements can be added (this causes overflow).
If the stack is empty and we try to remove an element, it causes underflow.
It is usually implemented using a normal array with fixed size.
Example: Creating a stack of size 10 using an array.
Dynamic Size Stack
A dynamic size stack can increase and decrease in size as needed.
If the stack becomes full, it automatically increases its capacity.
When elements are removed, memory can also reduce automatically.
It can be implemented using:
-> Linked List → size changes easily.
-> Dynamic Array (like vector in C++ or ArrayList in Java) → resizes automatically.
Example: Stack created using linked list or dynamic array.    
