1. Simple Queue (Linear Queue)
•It is the basic type of queue.
•Insertion is done at the rear end.
•Deletion is done from the front end.
•It follows FIFO (First In First Out) principle.
•It is easy to implement using array or linked list.
•Disadvantage: Empty spaces at front cannot be reused, 
causing memory wastage.
Engineer dude learning
Engineer dude learning
Enginee
Engin
Engin
Engin

2. Circular Queue
•In circular queue, the last 
position is connected to the 
first position.
•It forms a circular structure.
•It allows reuse of empty 
spaces.
•It avoids memory wastage.
•Used in CPU scheduling and 
buffering.
Engineer dude learning
Engineer dude learning
Enginee
Engin
Engin
Engin

Insertion means adding an 
element at the rear of the 
circular queue.
Steps:
•Check if the queue is full.
•If full, show Queue Overflow.
•If queue is empty, set front = 
rear = 0.
•Otherwise, move rear using 
circular condition:
rear = (rear + 1) % MAX
•Insert the element at 
queue[rear].
Insertion in Circular Queue (Enqueue)
Step 1: Start
Step 2: Check if (front == 0 AND rear 
== MAX-1) OR (rear + 1 == front)
Step 3: If true, print "Queue Overflow" 
and Stop
Step 4: If front == -1, set front = 0 and 
rear = 0
Step 5: Else set rear = (rear + 1) % MAX
Step 6: Insert item at queue[rear]
Step 7: Stop
Engineer dude learning
Engineer dude learning
Enginee
Engin
Engin
Engin

Deletion means removing an 
element from the front of the circular 
queue.
Steps:
•Check if the queue is empty.
•If empty, show Queue Underflow.
•Remove the element from 
queue[front].
•If only one element was present, set 
front = rear = -1.
•Otherwise, move front using circular 
condition:
front = (front + 1) % MAX
Deletion in Circular Queue (Dequeue)
Step 1: Start
Step 2: Check if front == -1
Step 3: If true, print "Queue Underflow" 
and Stop
Step 4: Set item = queue[front]
Step 5: If front == rear, set front = rear = 
-1
Step 6: Else set front = (front + 1) % 
MAX
Step 7: Return item
Step 8: Stop
